 mill ca.1645 near New Haven","body":"Built a mill ca.1645 near New Haven, later the site of Eli Whitney's cotton gin manufacturing establishment","migrated_from":"historical_significance"},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"His wife Mary Tapp's sister Jane married Governor","body":"His wife Mary Tapp's sister Jane married Governor Robert Treat — son John's will calls Treat \"my honorable uncle\"","migrated_from":"historical_significance"},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"Enrolled as \"Free Planter\" of Milford Nov 29","body":"Enrolled as \"Free Planter\" of Milford Nov 29, 1639","migrated_from":"historical_significance"},{"number":6,"category":"business","header":"Eli Whitney built on his millsite","body":"Fowler raised the colony’s first grist mill in 1645 at the falls two miles above New Haven; the town bought it from him in 1659 for a hundred pounds. A century and a half later Eli Whitney put his arms factory on the same site — today’s Whitneyville."},{"number":7,"category":"family","header":"His wife’s sister married the Governor","body":"By 1645 he had married Mary Tapp, daughter of Edmund Tapp of Milford — whose sister Jane was the wife of Governor Robert Treat. His will asked that his second wife Elizabeth “continue to live with his children, to be a guide and help to them as a mother.”"}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X00098","display_label":"Both from Hertfordshire; both among Milford's Seven Pillars.","link_text":"Deacon Richard Platt"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Capt. William Fowler Jr.","first_name":"William","last_name":"Fowler","married_names":[],"suffix":"Jr."},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"career":[{"role":"Deputy","organization":"New Haven General Court","start_year":1643},{"role":"Captain","organization":"New Haven trainband"},{"role":"Miller","locatio